Unfortunately, time travel in BigQuery doesn't work with the TRUNCATE statement.
The TRUNCATE statement in BigQuery is a DDL (Data Definition Language) operation that removes all rows from a table but does not log the row deletions for historical querying purposes. Since it doesn't leave a record of the deleted data in a way that BigQuery's time travel feature can track, you cannot use the FOR SYSTEM_TIME AS OF clause to retrieve data after a TRUNCATE operation.
Why Does Time Travel Not Work with TRUNCATE?
The TRUNCATE operation is a low-level operation that essentially resets the table by removing all data in it, but BigQuery doesn't preserve detailed historical records of what was deleted in this specific case.
Time travel works by leveraging historical versions of individual rows in a table, not the entire dataset. When rows are deleted via a TRUNCATE, that operation doesn't generate a historical version of the table's rows for BigQuery to query using time travel.
Time travel in BigQuery does not work with the DROP statement either.
The reason for this is similar to why it doesn't work with TRUNCATE: when you drop a table (using the DROP statement), the entire table is permanently removed from BigQuery, including its schema and data. Since DROP is a DDL operation, it removes the table and its associated metadata entirely. This means that BigQuery cannot track or preserve the table's data in a way that would allow you to use time travel to access it after the drop.
Why Time Travel Doesn't Work with DROP:
Table Removal: DROP deletes the table and all its contents, including its schema. There's no "historical version" of the table available after it has been dropped, so it becomes impossible to query its previous state.
Metadata Loss: Since the table is removed from the system, all associated metadata (such as the data and schema) is erased, leaving no record for BigQuery to refer to for time travel purposes.




